    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-24T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-24T14:00:00-05:00" n="114"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/6–2453: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 114<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Republic of China</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d114fn1">Drafted by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority <gloss target="#t_niact1"
                                >niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-24T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 24, 1953—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1077. Eyes only <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">Rankin</persName> from Secretary. In
                    view G’mo’s apparent backing of <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d114fn2">President of the Republic of Korea <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Syngman Rhee</persName>.</note> you should quickly in
                    your own words informally and in highest secrecy let G’mo know that <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s attempt to force US troops to fight
                    indefinitely in Korea at <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s behest
                    will not succeed. Plans are being formulated so that if <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> persists responsibility for Korea will be
                    left wholly to <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> forces as <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> suggests with consequent withdrawal of
                        <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> forces. We believe this will be
                    disastrous for Korea but see no alternative to <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName>’s absolute refusal to accept armistice and his threat to
                    withdraw his forces from <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> on a few hours’
                    notice. Effect of military disaster to <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> in
                    Korea and possible US withdrawal from Korea would doubtless require
                    reconsideration of US–Formosa policy with result not now predictable.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d114fn3">Telegram 1329 from Taipei, June 25, reported that <persName
                            corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName> had been informed of the contents
                        of this telegram and had made no comment, but that Foreign Minister
                            <persName corresp="#p_YGKCYK1">Yeh</persName> had informed <persName
                            corresp="#p_JHP1">Jones</persName> confidentially that no exchange of
                        views with the Korean Government had taken place on the subject.
                        (795.00/6–2553)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
